# C ABI contract

> TODO: document the `eunoia-capi` C ABI seam for native bindings.
>
> This is the boundary used by hosts whose only Rust-interop path is a
> C ABI — Julia today (via `ccall`/`Libdl`), and potentially Go (cgo),
> C/C++, Zig, etc. Hosts with a native Rust-binding framework
> (JavaScript via wasm-bindgen, Python via PyO3/maturin, R via extendr)
> bind the core directly and never touch this surface.
>
> When a second, non-first-party consumer appears, cover the parts a
> generated C header does not convey: the JSON shapes of inputs and
> outputs, canonical combination keying (`A`, `A&B`, `""` for
> complement), memory ownership across the boundary (who allocates, who
> frees returned strings), error encoding, and thread-safety. Until
> then `Eunoia.jl` is the reference implementation and the Rust source
> is authoritative.
